1
00:00:04,158 --> 00:00:08,547
We are at the United Nations in Geneva,
to interview Dr. Robert Glasser,

2
00:00:08,547 --> 00:00:11,626
Special Representative 
of the UN Secretary-General

3
00:00:11,626 --> 00:00:13,827
for Disaster Risk Reduction.

4
00:00:13,827 --> 00:00:17,095
Dr. Glasser is heading 
the United Nations Office

5
00:00:17,095 --> 00:00:20,375
for Disaster Risk Reduction, UNISDR.

6
00:00:20,375 --> 00:00:24,638
UNISDR is the focal point in the UN system

7
00:00:24,638 --> 00:00:27,479
coordinating disaster
reduction activities,

8
00:00:27,479 --> 00:00:30,750
and ensuring synergies 
with regional organizations

9
00:00:30,750 --> 00:00:34,941
in the field of socio-economic development
and humanitarian action.

10
00:00:35,591 --> 00:00:38,511
So UNISDR is a UN organization

11
00:00:38,511 --> 00:00:43,481
that focuses on supporting
the reduction of disaster risk.

12
00:00:43,481 --> 00:00:46,991
And it uses, as its foundation,
an international agreement

13
00:00:46,991 --> 00:00:49,760
called the Sendai Framework 
for Disaster Risk [Reduction],

14
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:54,554
which countries signed in 2015,

15
00:00:54,554 --> 00:00:56,934


16
00:00:57,914 --> 00:01:02,013
So with that as the basis,
the scope of work involved

17
00:01:02,013 --> 00:01:05,623
in implementing the Sendai Framework
to reduce disaster risk is enormous.

18
00:01:05,623 --> 00:01:10,115
It ranges from early warning 
and preparedness,

19
00:01:10,115 --> 00:01:12,891
and even work within disasters,

20
00:01:12,891 --> 00:01:17,491
to incorporating risk reduction measures

21
00:01:17,491 --> 00:01:20,576
as part of core economic 
planning and investment.

22
00:01:20,576 --> 00:01:25,095
It focuses on large-scale 
sudden-onset disasters,

23
00:01:25,095 --> 00:01:28,966
protracted disasters, 
slow-onset disasters.

24
00:01:28,966 --> 00:01:33,757
It focuses on large-scale, national scale,
sub-national scale,

25
00:01:33,757 --> 00:01:38,518
and it focuses on multiple hazards,
like pandemics,

26
00:01:38,518 --> 00:01:41,417
or radiological nuclear reactor meltdowns,

27
00:01:41,417 --> 00:01:45,679
or climate change, earthquakes, and so on.

28
00:01:45,679 --> 00:01:50,629
So it is such a broad agenda
and in every single one of those areas

29
00:01:50,629 --> 00:01:54,525
there are significant needs 
for science and technology.

30
00:01:54,525 --> 00:01:57,691
To give you a few examples:
climate change.

31
00:01:57,691 --> 00:02:01,808
Climate change is projected as actually 
already having an impact

32
00:02:01,808 --> 00:02:04,478
on extreme weather events,
a major hazard,

33
00:02:04,478 --> 00:02:08,061
particularly in developing countries
but in wealthy countries as well.

34
00:02:08,061 --> 00:02:12,531
We need to understand better
how climate is going to change,

35
00:02:12,531 --> 00:02:13,810
what patterns it will take,

36
00:02:13,810 --> 00:02:19,250
what impacts the release of CO2,

37
00:02:19,250 --> 00:02:24,061
of greenhouse gas emissions, will have
on tipping points in the climate system.

38
00:02:24,067 --> 00:02:28,463
We need to understand 
what impact global warming will have

39
00:02:28,463 --> 00:02:32,434
on the frequency and severity,
or patterns of El Niño, La Niña events,

40
00:02:32,434 --> 00:02:37,822
which are the key source 
of weather variability around the world.

41
00:02:38,812 --> 00:02:42,402
So if you just focus on climate change,

42
00:02:42,402 --> 00:02:44,103
understanding those dynamics

43
00:02:44,103 --> 00:02:47,383
are an enormous challenge for science
as we've seen.

44
00:02:47,383 --> 00:02:51,013
If you look at other levels of detail,
if you focus on, say,

45
00:02:51,013 --> 00:02:55,215
the impacts of extreme weather, 
